<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="115" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="115">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="115">
The species epithet is in honour of Mary Alice Eleanor Richards (also known from her collection labels as Mrs H.M. Richards), who collected extensively in Africa from 1951 to 1974 (Polhill and Polhill 2015). Of our new species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Veranso-Libalah &amp; G. Kadereit" authorityYear="2017" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Argyrella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Argyrella richardsiae" order="Myrtales" pageId="2" pageNumber="115" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="richardsiae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="115">Argyrella richardsiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, she made a collection which is cited above in 'Additional specimens 
<normalizedToken originalValue="examined’">examined'</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="115" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="115">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="115">
This species is evidently endemic to the wet miombo woodlands of Mpanda district, southwestern Tanzania and Huambo province, central Angola (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Distribution map of Argyrella species." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.82.12914.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/143175" pageId="2" pageNumber="115">2</figureCitation>
). Miombo woodland is a significant biome covering about 10% of the African landmass (
<bibRefCitation author="White, F" journalOrPublisher="Natural Resources Research (Paris)" pageId="5" pageNumber="118" pagination="1 - 356" refId="B19" refString="White, F, 1983. The vegetation of Africa. A descriptive memoir to accompany the UNESCO/AETFAT/UNSO vegetation map of Africa. Natural Resources Research (Paris) 20: 1 - 356" title="The vegetation of Africa. A descriptive memoir to accompany the UNESCO / AETFAT / UNSO vegetation map of Africa." volume="20" year="1983">White 1983</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell, B" journalOrPublisher="CIFOR, Bogor" pageId="4" pageNumber="117" publicationUrl="http://www.cifor.org/publications/pdf_files/books/miombo.pdf" refId="B2" refString="Campbell, B, Frost, P, Bron, N, 1996. Miombo woodlands and their use: overview and key issues. In: The Miombo in Transition: Woodlands and Welfare in Africa. CIFOR, Bogor, http://www.cifor.org/publications/pdf_files/books/miombo.pdf" title="Miombo woodlands and their use: overview and key issues" url="http://www.cifor.org/publications/pdf_files/books/miombo.pdf" volumeTitle="The Miombo in Transition: Woodlands and Welfare in Africa." year="1996">Campbell et al. 1996</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell, BM" journalOrPublisher="CIFOR, Bogor, Indonesia" pageId="4" pageNumber="117" publicationUrl="http://www.cifor.org/miombo/docs/Campbell_BarriersandOpportunities.pdf" refId="B3" refString="Campbell, BM, Angelsen, A, Cunningham, A, Katerere, Y, Sitoe, A, Wunder, S, 2007. Miombo woodlands - opportunities and barriers to sustainable forest management. CIFOR, Bogor, Indonesia, http://www.cifor.org/miombo/docs/Campbell_BarriersandOpportunities.pdf" title="Miombo woodlands - opportunities and barriers to sustainable forest management" url="http://www.cifor.org/miombo/docs/Campbell_BarriersandOpportunities.pdf" year="2007">2007</bibRefCitation>
). Miombo woodlands are mainly found in southern and central African countries, and are the dominant vegetation component of Angola, Zambia, Tanzania, Malawi, Mozambique and Zimbabwe (
<bibRefCitation author="Malmer, A" journalOrPublisher="Working Papers of the Finnish Forest Research Institute" pageId="4" pageNumber="117" pagination="34 - 42" publicationUrl="http://www.metla.fi/julkaisut/workingpapers/2007/mwp050-05.pdf" refId="B14" refString="Malmer, A, 2007. General ecological features of miombo woodlands and considerations for utilization and management. Working Papers of the Finnish Forest Research Institute 50: 34 - 42, http://www.metla.fi/julkaisut/workingpapers/2007/mwp050-05.pdf" title="General ecological features of miombo woodlands and considerations for utilization and management." url="http://www.metla.fi/julkaisut/workingpapers/2007/mwp050-05.pdf" volume="50" year="2007">Malmer 2007</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="White, F" journalOrPublisher="Natural Resources Research (Paris)" pageId="5" pageNumber="118" pagination="1 - 356" refId="B19" refString="White, F, 1983. The vegetation of Africa. A descriptive memoir to accompany the UNESCO/AETFAT/UNSO vegetation map of Africa. Natural Resources Research (Paris) 20: 1 - 356" title="The vegetation of Africa. A descriptive memoir to accompany the UNESCO / AETFAT / UNSO vegetation map of Africa." volume="20" year="1983">White 1983</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell, B" journalOrPublisher="CIFOR, Bogor" pageId="4" pageNumber="117" publicationUrl="http://www.cifor.org/publications/pdf_files/books/miombo.pdf" refId="B2" refString="Campbell, B, Frost, P, Bron, N, 1996. Miombo woodlands and their use: overview and key issues. In: The Miombo in Transition: Woodlands and Welfare in Africa. CIFOR, Bogor, http://www.cifor.org/publications/pdf_files/books/miombo.pdf" title="Miombo woodlands and their use: overview and key issues" url="http://www.cifor.org/publications/pdf_files/books/miombo.pdf" volumeTitle="The Miombo in Transition: Woodlands and Welfare in Africa." year="1996">Campbell et al. 1996</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell, BM" journalOrPublisher="CIFOR, Bogor, Indonesia" pageId="4" pageNumber="117" publicationUrl="http://www.cifor.org/miombo/docs/Campbell_BarriersandOpportunities.pdf" refId="B3" refString="Campbell, BM, Angelsen, A, Cunningham, A, Katerere, Y, Sitoe, A, Wunder, S, 2007. Miombo woodlands - opportunities and barriers to sustainable forest management. CIFOR, Bogor, Indonesia, http://www.cifor.org/miombo/docs/Campbell_BarriersandOpportunities.pdf" title="Miombo woodlands - opportunities and barriers to sustainable forest management" url="http://www.cifor.org/miombo/docs/Campbell_BarriersandOpportunities.pdf" year="2007">2007</bibRefCitation>
). They are mainly dominated by 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Brachystegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Brachystegia" order="Fabales" pageId="2" pageNumber="115" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="115">Brachystegia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Benth., 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pellegrin" authorityYear="1943" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Julbernardia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Julbernardia" order="Fabales" pageId="2" pageNumber="115" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="115">Julbernardia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Pellegr. and 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Leguminosae" genus="Isoberlinia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Isoberlinia" order="Fabales" pageId="2" pageNumber="115" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="115">Isoberlinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Craib &amp; Stapf trees of the subfamily 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Leguminosae" genus="Isoberlinia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Fabales" pageId="2" pageNumber="115" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Caesalpinioideae">Caesalpinioideae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Leguminosae" genus="Isoberlinia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Fabales" pageId="2" pageNumber="115" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="family">Leguminosae</taxonomicName>
. The wet miombo is found in areas of more than 1000 mm annual rainfall with an elevation of 1000-2500 m. A predominant wet miombo woodland vegetation is composed of riverine woodland along watercourses and marshes in poorly drained and/or low-lying areas, mainly characterised by alluvial soils (
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell, BM" journalOrPublisher="CIFOR, Bogor, Indonesia" pageId="4" pageNumber="117" publicationUrl="http://www.cifor.org/miombo/docs/Campbell_BarriersandOpportunities.pdf" refId="B3" refString="Campbell, BM, Angelsen, A, Cunningham, A, Katerere, Y, Sitoe, A, Wunder, S, 2007. Miombo woodlands - opportunities and barriers to sustainable forest management. CIFOR, Bogor, Indonesia, http://www.cifor.org/miombo/docs/Campbell_BarriersandOpportunities.pdf" title="Miombo woodlands - opportunities and barriers to sustainable forest management" url="http://www.cifor.org/miombo/docs/Campbell_BarriersandOpportunities.pdf" year="2007">Campbell et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="http://dx.doi.org/10.1155/2015/459102" author="Lupala, ZJ" journalOrPublisher="Adansonia" pageId="4" pageNumber="117" refId="B13" refString="Lupala, ZJ, Lusambo, LP, Ngaga, YM, Makatta, AA, 2015. http://dx.doi.org/10.1155/2015/459102" url="http://dx.doi.org/10.1155/2015/459102" year="2015">Lupala et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
). Also, wet miombo has higher tree height (typically&gt; 15 m) and higher floristic diversity which mainly occurs in the northern part of miombo distribution: eastern Angola, northern Zambia, southwestern Tanzania and central Malawi (
<bibRefCitation author="Frost, PGH" editor="Campbell, B" journalOrPublisher="CIFOR, Bogor, Indonesia" pageId="4" pageNumber="117" pagination="11 - 57" refId="B8" refString="Frost, PGH, 1996. The ecology of miombo woodlands. In: Campbell, B, Ed., The miombo in transition: woodlands and welfare in Africa. CIFOR, Bogor, Indonesia: 11 - 57" title="The ecology of miombo woodlands." volumeTitle="The miombo in transition: woodlands and welfare in Africa." year="1996">Frost 1996</bibRefCitation>
). It is likely that 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="A." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="A. richardsiae" order="Myrtales" pageId="2" pageNumber="115" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="richardsiae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="115">A. richardsiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also occurs in wet miombo woodlands of southern Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), northern Zambia and southern Malawi and not just disjunctly between Angola and Tanzania. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Veranso-Libalah &amp; G. Kadereit" authorityYear="2017" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Argyrella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Argyrella richardsiae" order="Myrtales" pageId="2" pageNumber="115" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="richardsiae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="115">Argyrella richardsiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
like the other 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Argyrella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Argyrella" order="Myrtales" pageId="2" pageNumber="115" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="115">Argyrella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species grows in marshes.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-Zenodo-Dep="993433" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.82.12914.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/143175" pageId="2" pageNumber="115" start="Figure 2" startId="F2">
